{%- comment -%}
  Home project intro — a quiet, centered invitation to a project (currently the Great Books).

  Deliberately plain: eyebrow, serif heading, one line, one text link with an arrow. No cards,
  no featured guides, no covers. The homepage introduces the project; the project page sells
  the guides.

  Optional background image with a dark overlay (currently the Great Books bookshelf hero,
  reused from the Great Books page). With an image set, the section flips to light-on-dark;
  without one it stays quiet on white. Both states are supported — don't assume the image.
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- assign bg = section.settings.image -%}
{%- assign has_bg = false -%}
{%- if bg != blank -%}{%- assign has_bg = true -%}{%- endif -%}

<section
  class="ra-section ra-project-intro{% if has_bg %} ra-project-intro--media{% endif %}"
  id="ProjectIntro-{{ section.id }}"
>
  {%- if has_bg -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      Desktop and mobile get genuinely different crops of the same photograph — a wide
      two-shelf frame, and a portrait crop of the lower shelf. A <picture> with a media
      query swaps the file itself; object-position alone can't reframe a photo this
      differently. If no mobile image is set, mobile falls back to the desktop file.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <div class="ra-project-intro__bg" aria-hidden="true">
      <picture>
        {%- if section.settings.mobile_image != blank -%}
          <source
            media="(max-width: 989px)"
            srcset="
              {{ section.settings.mobile_image | image_url: width: 600 }} 600w,
              {{ section.settings.mobile_image | image_url: width: 800 }} 800w,
              {{ section.settings.mobile_image | image_url: width: 1000 }} 1000w
            "
            sizes="100vw"
          >
        {%- endif -%}
        {{
          bg
          | image_url: width: 2000
          | image_tag:
            class: 'ra-project-intro__image',
            widths: '750, 1100, 1500, 2000',
            sizes: '100vw',
            loading: 'eager',
            alt: ''
        }}
      </picture>
    </div>
  {%- endif -%}

  <div class="ra-container-sm ra-text-center ra-project-intro__inner">
    {%- comment -%}
      With an image, the copy sits inside a translucent panel rather than on a full-bleed
      scrim: the shelf stays sharp and readable across the whole frame, and only the copy's
      own footprint is darkened. Without an image the panel is inert (no background, no
      border) and the section reads as plain centered text on white.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <div class="ra-project-intro__panel">
      {%- comment -%}
        The pool of shade wraps THIS block only — heading, rules, eyebrow, lede. The button sits
        outside it and carries its own fill, so it reads as a button rather than a shape floating
        in a cloud of shadow.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <div class="ra-project-intro__copy">
      {%- comment -%}
        Over a photograph the eyebrow drops BELOW the heading and sits between two red rules —
        a masthead line, not a label floating above the title. Without an image it stays where
        an eyebrow normally goes, above the heading, with no rules.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- if section.settings.eyebrow != blank and has_bg == false -%}
        <p class="ra-section-header__eyebrow">{{ section.settings.eyebrow | escape }}</p>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- comment -%}
        Heading is intentionally NOT escaped: it accepts a little inline markup so a single
        word can be set in italic (e.g. "Built <em>the</em> West"). Admin-authored only.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- if section.settings.heading != blank -%}
        <h2 class="ra-section-header__title">{{ section.settings.heading }}</h2>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- if has_bg -%}
        <span class="ra-project-intro__rule" aria-hidden="true"></span>

        {%- if section.settings.eyebrow != blank -%}
          <p class="ra-section-header__eyebrow ra-project-intro__eyebrow--ruled">
            {{- section.settings.eyebrow | escape -}}
          </p>
          <span class="ra-project-intro__rule ra-project-intro__rule--under" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        {%- endif -%}
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- if section.settings.text != blank -%}
        <div class="ra-project-intro__text">{{ section.settings.text }}</div>
      {%- endif -%}
      </div>

      {%- comment -%}
        Over a photograph this is a real (if quiet) button, outside the pool of shade.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- if section.settings.button_label != blank and section.settings.button_link != blank -%}
        <div class="ra-project-intro__actions">
          <a class="ra-text-link" href="{{ section.settings.button_link }}">
            {{- section.settings.button_label | escape -}}
          </a>
        </div>
      {%- endif -%}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

{%- style -%}
  .ra-project-intro__text {
    margin-top: var(--ra-space-md);
    font-size: 19px;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--ra-color-muted);
  }

  .ra-project-intro__actions {
    margin-top: var(--ra-space-xl);
  }

  /* --- With a background image: a full-width feature, light text on dark ---
     Height is driven by min-height (not padding) so the copy is centered inside the image
     rather than stretching it. Tall enough to read as a destination section, not a divider.
     The margin below gives the feature room to finish before American Craftsmanship begins. */
  .ra-project-intro--media {
    position: relative;
    isolation: isolate;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    min-height: {{ section.settings.banner_height }}px;
    /* Padding is only a floor here — the copy is flex-centred inside min-height. Kept at 2xl
       so the now-airier text stack still sits inside 520px rather than growing the section. */
    padding-top: var(--ra-space-2xl);
    padding-bottom: var(--ra-space-2xl);
    /* Pulled up under the pillars above (which carry 72px of their own bottom padding) so the
       two read as one movement — the pillars name the Great Books, this shows them. The
       section below carries its own 72px of top padding, so this margin stays modest. */
    margin-top: calc(-1 * var(--ra-space-xl));
    margin-bottom: var(--ra-space-lg);
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  /* Large, restrained display type — this is a feature spread, not a banner. */
  /* The measure is capped in `em`, so it scales with the type: wide enough for two balanced
     lines ("Read the Books That / Built the West"), narrow enough that the last word can't be
     left stranded on a line of its own. */
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-section-header__title {
    font-size: clamp(42px, 5.8vw, 76px);
    line-height: 1.12;
    margin: 0 auto;
    max-width: 8.8em;
    text-wrap: balance;
  }

  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__text {
    font-size: 20px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    max-width: 30em;
    margin-top: 22px;
    margin-left: auto;
    margin-right: auto;
  }

  /* Stack with positive z-indexes, not z-index:-1 — a negative index on the media layer
     rendered it behind the section's own background box and the banner came out blank white. */
  /* The top and bottom edges dissolve into the page rather than stopping at a hard rule, so
     the feature reads as a plate on the page instead of a banner bolted to it. The fade is
     ~30px — enough to soften the line, not enough to look like a vignette. The mask covers
     the pool of shade too (it lives on this element's ::after), so they fade together. */
  .ra-project-intro__bg {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    z-index: 0;
    -webkit-mask-image: linear-gradient(
      to bottom,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55) 0,
      #000 10px,
      #000 calc(100% - 10px),
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55) 100%
    );
    mask-image: linear-gradient(
      to bottom,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55) 0,
      #000 10px,
      #000 calc(100% - 10px),
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55) 100%
    );
  }

  .ra-project-intro__bg picture {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
  }

  .ra-project-intro__image {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: {{ section.settings.focus_x }}% {{ section.settings.focus_y }}%;
  }

  /* The shelf carries the section, so it stays bright: only a whisper of a flat wash
     (the `overlay_opacity` setting, now low) to keep the whole frame from glaring, plus a
     soft elliptical pool of shade sized to the copy's own footprint. It has no edge — it
     fades to nothing well before the frame — so there's no panel, no box, no border. */
  /* The wash lives on a pseudo-element, not a child div: a theme rule elsewhere was
     computing `display: none` on the overlay div and the banner rendered unreadable. */
  .ra-project-intro__bg::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    z-index: 1;
    background: rgba(0, 0, 0, {{ section.settings.overlay_opacity | divided_by: 100.0 }});
  }

  /* Shade rides the copy, not the frame. Each element carries its own soft pool — sized to
     its own text because the boxes are inline-block, so they hug the words — instead of one
     big blob over the middle of the shelf. Every pool fades to nothing inside its own
     padding, so there is no edge to see, and lines that used to sit on bare image (the CTA,
     the eyebrow) now carry shade of their own. This also fixes mobile for free: the shade
     goes wherever the text goes, at any width. */
  /* ONE pool behind the whole group, not one per line. `display: table` makes the panel
     shrink-wrap its own text (block-level, so no baseline gaps), and the generous padding is
     transparent room for the gradient to die out inside its own box.

     The vertical radius stays UNDER 50% on purpose: a radial-gradient's percentages are radii
     relative to the box, so anything over 50% gets clipped by the box edge mid-fade — which is
     exactly what draws a hard horizontal line. At 46%/96% the pool reaches zero inside the
     padding, so there is no edge anywhere. */
  /* The copy sits inside `.ra-container-sm` (720px) — with the pool's padding that left only
     ~570px of text width, which is what pushed the heading to three lines and the lede to two.
     The feature overrides the container: the copy gets room to break the way it should. */
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__inner {
    max-width: 1060px;
  }

  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__panel {
    max-width: 1000px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  /* The pool now hugs the copy only. `display: table` shrink-wraps it; the padding is
     transparent room for the gradient to die inside its own box (a vertical radius over 50%
     gets clipped by the box edge mid-fade — that's what draws a hard line). */
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__copy {
    display: table;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 84px 80px;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 62% 49% at 50% 50%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.76) 0%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.74) 40%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.62) 62%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.36) 78%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.14) 89%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0) 97%
    );
  }

  .ra-project-intro__panel {
    max-width: 620px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  /* One short red hairline under the heading — the only ornament in the section. */
  .ra-project-intro__rule {
    display: block;
    width: 84px;
    height: 2px;
    margin: 22px auto 0;
    background: #c62436;
  }

  /* One block of copy — the gaps stay modest, but each line gets room to breathe. */
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-section-header__eyebrow {
    margin: 0;
    letter-spacing: 0.26em;
  }

  /* The eyebrow now lives between the two rules, so its spacing is symmetrical and it needs
     no pool of its own — it sits in the middle of the group, where the shade is deepest. */
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__eyebrow--ruled {
    margin: 14px 0;
  }

  .ra-project-intro__rule--under {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  /* Negative, because the copy block's bottom padding is transparent fade-room, not spacing —
     without this the button would sit an extra ~80px adrift. */
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__actions {
    margin-top: -44px;
  }

  /* A button, but a quiet one: a hairline pill over the photograph. It carries its own fill —
     enough to hold the label against the spines now that it sits outside the pool of shade —
     and goes ink-on-white on hover, matching the primary button elsewhere on the site. */
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-text-link {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 10px;
    padding: 15px 32px;
    border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.62);
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.42);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: background 0.2s ease, border-color 0.2s ease, color 0.2s ease;
  }

  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-text-link:hover,
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-text-link:focus-visible {
    background: #fff;
    border-color: #fff;
    color: #111;
    text-shadow: none;
  }

  /* Gilded spines are the busiest possible backdrop, and the image is now bright — so each
     line carries its own shadow. This is what buys the contrast a flat overlay used to,
     without dimming the books. */
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-section-header__title {
    text-shadow: 0 2px 20px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.75), 0 1px 3px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
  }

  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__text,
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-section-header__eyebrow,
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-text-link {
    text-shadow: 0 1px 12px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.8), 0 1px 2px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
  }

  .ra-project-intro__inner {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
  }

  /* Desktop only: nudge the copy *down* off dead centre, so it sits across the lower shelf —
     the hero — and leaves the upper shelf and the glass line reading clearly above it.
     (This was a -24px lift when the photo was a single row of spines; the two-shelf frame
     wants the opposite.) A transform, so the section height and image framing don't move. */
  @media screen and (min-width: 990px) {
    .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__inner {
      transform: translateY(-140px);
    }
  }

  /* Over a photograph, every line is full white — the dimmed eyebrow (75%) and lede (88%)
     were costing real legibility for no design benefit. */
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-section-header__eyebrow,
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-section-header__title,
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__text,
  .ra-project-intro--media .ra-text-link {
    color: #fff;
  }

  @media screen and (max-width: 989px) {
    .ra-project-intro--media {
      min-height: {{ section.settings.banner_height | times: 0.72 | round }}px;
      margin-bottom: var(--ra-space-3xl);
    }
  }

  @media screen and (max-width: 749px) {
    /* Mobile is framed for its own crop (~0.81:1), not scaled off the desktop height. */
    .ra-project-intro--media {
      min-height: 480px;
      padding-top: var(--ra-space-lg);
      padding-bottom: var(--ra-space-lg);
      margin-bottom: var(--ra-space-2xl);
    }

    /* The pool needs less room to fade at this scale, and it works harder: a phone screen is
       small, bright and often held outdoors, so the copy needs more separation from the spines
       than it does on a desktop. */
    .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__panel {
      padding: 0;
    }

    .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__copy {
      padding: 64px 28px;
      background: radial-gradient(
        ellipse 66% 48% at 50% 50%,
        rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.86) 0%,
        rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.82) 38%,
        rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.68) 60%,
        rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.42) 76%,
        rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.16) 89%,
        rgba(0, 0, 0, 0) 97%
      );
    }

    .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__actions {
      margin-top: -32px;
    }


    .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__inner {
      transform: translateY(-26px);
    }

    .ra-project-intro--media .ra-section-header__title {
      font-size: 50px;
      line-height: 1.02;
    }

    .ra-project-intro--media .ra-project-intro__text {
      font-size: 17px;
    }
  }
{%- endstyle -%}

{% schema %}
{
  "name": "Home project intro",
  "tag": "section",
  "settings": [
    { "type": "text", "id": "eyebrow", "label": "Eyebrow", "default": "The Great Books Project" },
    { "type": "text", "id": "heading", "label": "Heading", "default": "Read What Built Civilization." },
    {
      "type": "richtext",
      "id": "text",
      "label": "Text",
      "default": "<p>A chronological reading journey through the books, ideas, and people that shaped the Western world.</p>"
    },
    { "type": "text", "id": "button_label", "label": "Button label", "default": "Explore the Great Books" },
    { "type": "text", "id": "button_link", "label": "Button link", "default": "/pages/great-books-project" },
    {
      "type": "image_picker",
      "id": "image",
      "label": "Background image",
      "info": "Optional. With an image, the section goes light-on-dark; without one it stays on white. Desktop crop — wide (~2.2:1)."
    },
    {
      "type": "image_picker",
      "id": "mobile_image",
      "label": "Mobile background image",
      "info": "Optional. A separate, portrait-ish crop (~0.85:1) used below 990px. Falls back to the desktop image if empty."
    },
    {
      "type": "range",
      "id": "banner_height",
      "label": "Feature height",
      "min": 200,
      "max": 900,
      "step": 10,
      "unit": "px",
      "default": 820
    },
    {
      "type": "range",
      "id": "overlay_opacity",
      "label": "Overlay darkness",
      "min": 0,
      "max": 80,
      "step": 5,
      "unit": "%",
      "default": 25
    },
    { "type": "range", "id": "focus_x", "label": "Image focus X", "min": 0, "max": 100, "step": 5, "unit": "%", "default": 50 },
    { "type": "range", "id": "focus_y", "label": "Image focus Y", "min": 0, "max": 100, "step": 5, "unit": "%", "default": 50 }
  ],
  "presets": [
    { "name": "Home project intro" }
  ]
}
{% endschema %}
